{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","author_sig":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","data":{"body":"Automated quality-enforcement audit slice completed 2026-07-19.\n\nExisting strengths:\n- Gerrit Verified reuses the same lint, type-check, pip-audit, and test workflow as branch CI; the matrix covers Python 3.11-3.13 and macOS.\n- Ruff is exactly pinned and gates E/F/W/I/UP/B plus BLE001, T201, and SIM115; mypy gates all 354 source files with a strictness ratchet.\n- Branch coverage has a 70 percent floor; module size has a locked 800-LOC hard cap; generated schema, prompt, env-var, CLI, MCP, docs-index, and config drift gates are blocking.\n- The LLM-Review lane makes gitleaks and the curated Semgrep-compatible High/Critical rules fail closed on changed files. CodeQL scans Python and JavaScript on main and weekly.\n- Clean-wheel, optional-extra, README golden-path, actionlint, zizmor release audit, and dependency-vulnerability checks materially strengthen packaging and CI reliability.\n\nPrioritized findings:\nHIGH 1. CodeQL is post-merge only: codeql.yml triggers on main push and weekly schedule, not on the exact Gerrit patchset, and uses only default queries. Add an exact-patchset pre-merge CodeQL lane, security-extended queries, and an explicit SARIF severity policy; keep the weekly full scan. CONTRIBUTING currently claims mirror PR coverage that the workflow does not declare.\nHIGH 2. The pre-merge scanner host is not reproducible: Dockerfile.reviewbot resolves the latest gitleaks release dynamically and installs unconstrained semgrep; the base image is tag-only. Pin scanner versions, hashes, Python requirements, and image digests. Many non-release Actions also use mutable major tags; expand zizmor from release.yml to every workflow and SHA-pin third-party actions.\nHIGH 3. Dependency auditing is not reproducible or complete across extras: CI resolves unconstrained dependency floors on every run and pip-audit covers the dev closure, while reviewbot, ui, eval, tracing, and grounding extras are not all audited as shipped combinations. Commit a CI/dev lock or hashed constraints, install frozen, and audit core plus a supported union of production extras.\nMEDIUM 4. The job named import-linter is an AST optional-dependency guard, not an architectural dependency-direction gate. Add Import Linter or equivalent contracts for stable layer boundaries and cycles, based on docs/architecture.md.\nMEDIUM 5. The metric detector declares max_complexity 15, but engine_b_backends implements only file LOC and explicitly leaves function complexity as follow-up. Add Ruff C901 or a pinned lizard/complexity gate with a no-new-violations baseline; keep the 800-LOC cap.\nMEDIUM 6. Mypy remains permissive outside rebar.graph and rebar.grounding: ignore_missing_imports is global and only those packages disallow untyped definitions. Continue the existing shrink-only ratchet and add high-signal global flags such as warn_unused_ignores, warn_redundant_casts, no_implicit_optional, strict_equality, and disallow_any_generics after baselining.\nMEDIUM 7. Coverage has seven points of intentional headroom and omits subprocess-driven CLI coverage; mutation testing is configured but absent from CI and mutmut is not a declared dev dependency. Enable coverage subprocess patching, add changed-line coverage, raise the floor near the measured baseline, and run bounded scheduled mutation tests with per-module minimum scores.\nMEDIUM 8. Ruff can add high-signal families incrementally rather than enable ALL: S, ASYNC, DTZ, RUF, and a calibrated complexity rule. Expand the tiny curated Semgrep ruleset first in advisory mode, then promote proven rules.\nMEDIUM 9. Local hooks are not hermetic: pre-commit uses language system and Make calls ambient ruff and mypy. In this audit, ambient make lint used a different Ruff behavior on the ignored generated build-info file and ambient make typecheck could not find mypy, while direct .venv binaries passed. Route Make and hooks through the repository environment or a frozen runner.\n\nVerification:\n- Direct .venv Ruff check and format-check passed.\n- Direct .venv mypy passed over 354 source files.\n- Nine focused ratchet/actionlint/module-size tests passed.\n- Security-rule freshness passed at 19 days against a 90-day cadence.\n- Local semgrep could not initialize its X509 trust store; gitleaks 8.30.1 was present; lizard and scc were absent. These local facts do not substitute for the separately built production review-bot image.\n\nNo production files were modified."},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1784486250339723001,"uuid":"7c90448d-9ffb-47b6-a3c5-e19756413725"}